  "prompt": "In pregnancy, why is tetracycline contraindicated?",
  "response": "Tetracycline is contraindicated in pregnancy, particularly during the second and third trimesters, for several important reasons:\n\n1. Dental effects:\n- Causes permanent yellow-brown discoloration of developing teeth\n- Can cause enamel hypoplasia (defective tooth development)\n- Affects both primary and permanent teeth\n\n2. Bone development:\n- Inhibits bone growth\n- Can cause impaired bone calcification\n- Potentially leads to reduced bone growth in the fetus\n\n3. Mechanism of action:\n- Chelates calcium ions\n- Binds to calcium in developing teeth and bones\n- Interferes with normal mineralization process\n\n4. Long-term consequences:\n- Irreversible dental staining\n- Potential permanent developmental abnormalities\n- Risk of compromised tooth and bone structure\n\n5. Timing of risk:\n- Most significant during tooth and bone formation stages\n- Highest risk in second and third trimesters\n- Some risk in early pregnancy\n\nThese potential teratogenic effects make tetracycline a Category D drug (positive evidence of human fetal risk) and should be avoided during pregnancy to prevent potential harm to the developing fetus.",
